1. cs.DS (Discrete Mathematics): The problem of Capacitated Domination involves finding a minimum-sized set of vertices that can cover all of the graph's demand without exceeding any of the capacities. This is a discrete optimization problem and falls under the scope of Discrete Mathematics. 
2. cs.CG (Computational Geometry): The paper specifically looks at Capacitated Domination in unweighted planar graphs. Planar graphs are a subset of graphs that can be embedded in the plane without any edges crossing. This property makes them interesting from a computational geometry perspective, and hence this paper could be categorized under cs.CG. 
3. cs.DM (Data Structures and Algorithms): The paper presents a polynomial-time approximation scheme for Capacitated Domination in unweighted planar graphs when the maximum capacity and maximum demand are bounded. This involves designing efficient algorithms and data structures, which falls under the scope of cs.DM. 
4. cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory): The problem of Capacitated Domination involves finding a minimum-sized set of vertices that can cover all of the graph's demand without exceeding any of the capacities. This is a game-theoretic problem where the objective is to minimize the cost of covering the demand. Hence, this paper could be categorized under cs.GT.
